Analyzing data from the World Happiness Report¶

We will be analyzing data from the world happiness report. More information is provided in the tutorial.
By: Ryan Pham, Eric Strauss

Introduction¶

Welcome to our data science tutorial. In this tutorial, we will be going through the data science pipeline where we will collect data, manage and represent the data, explore and analyze the data, perform hypothesis testing and machine learning, and communicate the insights gained. For this tutorial, we will be exploring data from the world happiness report. The world happiness report ranks each country based on a happiness score which they calculate based on their formula. We think this is a good dataset because we can explore how each variable used to calculate happiness is correlated. We can also explore how happiness changes over time since we have access to multiple reports that were released each year (2015 - 2021).

Set Up¶

Below are packages that we will use in this tutorial

Representing the Data¶

To represent the data we will be using read_csv, which is part of the Pandas library, to create data frames. To use read_cvs you need to pass in the name of your csv files. For our tutorial, we will be creating 6 data frames. Each data frame will represent a year between 2015 to 2021.

Cleaning the data¶

After creating the data frames we need to clean our data. Luckily for us, the data in our data frames are pretty clean and there are no missing values. However, the columns of the data frames need to be fixed. Certain data frames have more columns than others and the name of the columns vary between the years. Country name, Happiness Score, Economy, Family Life, Expectancy, Freedom, Government Corruption Generosity, Dystopia Residual. Changing the name of the columns will make it easier for us to access the data frame. If we keep the names different for each data frame it can get confusing when we try to access one data frame with the name of a column from a different data frame.

To rename a column we will use the rename method. In the rename method, we will name the columns current name followed by the columns new name. For example:

dataframe.rename(column = {Column Old Name:Column New Name}

We will also be dropping columns that are not found in all of the data frames. We did this to make sure all of the data frames have the same information. To drop a column we used the drop method. For example:

dataframe.drop(columns=["column1","column2", "column3"])

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

The next step of this tutorial is to explore our data. Happiness is not something that is easily quantified. The World Happiness Report used six factors to calculate each countrys happiness score. The factors are economy, family life, expectancy, freedom, government corruption, and generosity. The first thing we wanted to do when we saw the data was to see if there was a correlation between each of the factors to happiness. To do this we decided to use a spearman correlation matrix. This matrix will compare each variable of the dataset to each other. The final result will be a colored matrix. Darker blue colors suggest a high correlation. Lighter blue colors suggest a lower correlation. Light yellow colors suggest a negative correlation.

In [26]:

Based on our heatmap we found that economy, family, and life expectancy had the highest correlation to the happiness score. We also noticed that generosity had a low correlation to the happiness score.

Finding the number of times a country appears in the top 10¶

We also decided to look at the top ten countries in terms of happiness. We wanted to see how many times a country will appear in the top ten between 2015 to 2021. We calculated this by using a dictionary. The key is the country and the value is the number of times it appears in the top ten.

In [33]:
dict = {}
first10_2015 = df2015["Country name"]
first10_2016 = df2016["Country name"]
first10_2017 = df2017["Country name"]
first10_2018 = df2018["Country name"]
first10_2019 = df2019["Country name"]
first10_2020 = df2021["Country name"]
first10_2021 = df2021["Country name"]

x = list(first10_2015[:10]) + list(first10_2016[:10]) + list(first10_2017[:10]) + list(first10_2018[:10]) + list(first10_2019[:10]) + list(first10_2020[:10]) + list(first10_2021[:10])   

# Find the number of times a country appears in the top 10
for i in x:
    if i in dict:
        dict[i] += 1
    else:
        dict[i] = 1
print(dict)

Hypothesis Testing¶

The next step of our tutorial is to perform hypothesis testing. Hypothesis testing is used to assess the plausibility of a hypothesis using data. In hypothesis testing, we have two hypotheses: the null hypothesis and the alternative hypothesis. A null hypothesis means there is no relationship. In our hypothesis test, we want to be able to reject the null hypothesis. To reject a null hypothesis we need two values: a p-value and a significance level. The p-value will be calculated while the significance value is set by you. If the p-value is greater than or equal to the significance level, then you will not reject the null hypothesis. If the p-value is smaller than the significance level then you can reject the null hypothesis. For this tutorial, we will be using a significance of 0.05. We will also be using the scipy library.

United States Generosity¶

For our first test, we will check if there is a relationship between the United States generosity score and the other variables used to calculate happiness (Economy, Family, and Life Expectancy), the happiness score, and time.

Null Hypothesis¶

There is no relationship between the United States generosity score and its happiness score.
There is no relationship between the United States generosity score and its economy score.
There is no relationship between the United States generosity score and its family Score.
There is no relationship between the United States generosity score and its life expectancy Score.
There is no relationship between the United States generosity score and the year.

In [44]:
#Remove 2020 and 2021 because data elements are under different scales.

us_table = us_table[us_table['Year'] != 2021]
X = us_table.drop(['Generosity','Country name'], axis=1)
Y = us_table['Generosity']

#Use library to calculate p values.
for i in X.columns: 
    _, _, _, p_value, _ = stats.linregress(X[i],Y)
    print("P_Value ", p_value, "For ", i)

P_Value  0.04044607756823605 For  Year

The P-value for happiness score and time are less than 0.05 therefore we can reject the null hypothesis for those variables. The following null hypothesis can be rejected:

 There is no relationship between the United States generosity score and its happiness score.
 There is no relationship between the United States generosity score and the year.

We do not reject the null hypothesis for the economy, family, and life expectancy because the p-values are greater than 0.05. We do not reject the following null hypothesis:

 There is no relationship between the United States generosity score and its economy score.
 There is no relationship between the United States generosity score and its family Score.
 There is no relationship between the United States generosity score and its life expectancy Score.

United States Happiness¶

For our second test, we will compare the United States happiness score with variables used to compute happiness (Economy, Family, Life Expectancy, Generosity) and time.

Null Hypothesis¶

There is no relationship between the United States happiness score and its economy score.
There is no relationship between the United States happiness score and its family Score.
There is no relationship between the United States happiness score and its life expectancy Score.
There is no relationship between the United States happiness score and its generosity score.
There is no relationship between the United States happiness score and the year.

Machine Learning¶

For the last part of the tutorial, we will be using machine learning to predict happiness values. To do this we first need to create a linear regression. We will be using sklearn to create the linear regression. When we use a linear regression we assume 4 things:
 1. That a linear relationship exists
 2. Independence of residuals
 3. Constant Variance of residuals (this is known as 'Homoscedasticity')
 4. That the residuals are normally distributed (this is known as 'Normality')
To make sure these assumptions are met we will add an interaction term to our model. We als decided to use a random set of countries rather than looking at all of the countries since it can get messy.

    new_combo['Economy*'+s] = new_combo[s]*new_combo['Economy']

Conclusion / Insights Attained¶

In this tutorial, we were able to analyze data from the world happiness report using the data science pipeline. We used data visualization to see if there was a relationship between the happiness score and any of the variables used to calculate the score. Using a heat map, we found that there was a strong correlation between happiness scores and variables like the economy, family, and life expectancy. We also made plots visualizing the number of times countries showed up in the top 10 and the happiness score of the United States over time. We then used hypothesis testing to see if various relationship exists or not. One of the relationship we tested was between United State happiness score and variables used to calulate happiness + time. We found that there was a relationship and was able to reject the null hypothesis for the various factors. Lastly, we used machine learning to try to predict happiness values based on one of the variables used in the world happiness report. We decided to use the economy variable. Based on the graph of our model we found that the predicted happiness value will generally increase along with the economic value.
